These are the most common ways to monetize your platforms, but this will also heavily vary depending on the platform you’re on! Personally, brand collaborations were my biggest source of income when I was starting out and you can find my Brand Contact emails list & Influencer pitch templates linked in my description 🔗

The other day I was getting one of those mini anxiety episodes trying to fall asleep for hours (*sob* lmao) so I started reading some of my old journal entries, the oldest ones I had were from 2018. Just reading about the things I was stressing over that ended up having zero impact on my life and the people I was writing about who aren’t even in my life anymore is crazy and honestly very grounding. We always tend to over-stress the little things that we think are important in the moment, but time will tell how much those things will really impact our lives in the long run. That boy you cried over years ago, that internship offer you didn’t get, that class you failed that you swore would follow you for life (🙋🏻‍♀️) - in a few years they’ll likely just be memories to think about every once in a while. Don’t let something that won’t impact your life in 5 years affect your mood for more than 5 minutes (or at least try not to, doesn’t always work 100% but it helps a bit). I’m rooting for you! ☁️💡🤍

My full tech career path + salaries 👩🏻‍💻💵

As someone who didn’t know where to start when it came to salaries, negotiations, and the overall job search process in the beginning, I’m all for pay transparency and sharing the numbers 🙋🏻‍♀️, especially if it can help someone who’s currently in that same boat. I’ve made a few videos on my YouTube channel specifically on my interview & job search experience but hopefully this gave some insight into what some potential tech salaries can look like in your early career!

FYI this is not a brag post and I know there are SWEs and security analysts making more or less than this based on their sector, experience level, education, location, and various other factors. Always do research on salaries for any job you apply to and don’t be afraid to negotiate for what you’re worth.

Anyone else? 🥹🙋🏻‍♀️

It feels like there are so many things you can do and ways life can go that when you make one decision, it’s like you’re closing the door on another. I’m a firm believer that you can always make pivots in your life and pursue the paths you want to, even if they’re vastly different! It’s like living multiple lives in one 🤠

This view was on our way up hiking Angels Landing! Definitely made it to my top 3 hikes ever 🚐🏞️
Trying a few different hairstyles, now that I have slight bangs again 💇🏻‍♀️

How I got into cybersecurity 👩🏻‍💻
Following up on my reels on how much I make working in tech! I was open to lots of different roles when I was graduating and I also think that’s key when you’re just getting started in your career. You never know where that can take you! For me, these were the key things that helped me:
* Attending a career conference like the @anitab_org Grace Hopper Celebration👩‍🏭👩🏽‍💼👩🏻‍⚕️
* Getting my @comptiaofficial Security+ cert 📚
* Applying to jobs on the right sites! I use @builtin 💼 (also where I got my current job!)

I have my cyber security career resources linked in my bio! Good luck and let me know if you have any questions! 🤠

Dreamy views in Moab 🔸

It feels like such a dream to be able to work and travel at the same time, sometimes it’s a bit surreal still that we’re on this road trip. I think the biggest lesson that I’ve learned so far is that I suck at living in the present lol, I’ll be thinking about work while I’m hiking then during work hours, I’ll be stressing over all the things I have to do (or “get to do” tbh) after. There’s really no winning when either way, I don’t let myself live in the moment and just focus on what’s in front of me.

Something I got from my therapist that I’ve been using again is just making use of my five senses to be more present, aka: what do you feel, see, hear in your current environment. It honestly helps a lot when you’re feeling anxious about some distant thing in the future because most of the time, the things you worry about either don’t even happen or are never as bad as you think. All you have to worry about is what’s right here, right now. Hope this week treats you well 🤍

Never thought i’d be such a stan but Utah was one of the prettiest states I’ve ever seen 🫣 highlights from the top 5:
• Canyonlands National Park

• Capitol Reef

How to get into cybersecurity with no experience 👩🏻‍💻
Typically the process looks like this:
- Enroll in a cybersecurity beginner course or bootcamp (linked in my bio!)
- Get an entry level cert, the Security+ is the one I took and also what I recommend since it’s one of the most popular but I’m slightly biased, another option could be the GIAC GSEC cert 📚
- Do as many personal projects you can, in fact you can just ask chatgpt or bard to make you a beginner study guide for any projects you wanna do or specific tools you wanna learn how to use, definitely take advantage of them 🥸
- Using simulation tools like tryhackme, Hackthebox, and Letsdefend.io are great ways to get hands on experience on red team or blue team. You can sign up for Hackthebox using the link in my bio 💻

Lmk if you have any questions 🤠

The best cybersecurity career advice I’ve gotten from my mentors 👩🏻‍💻:
1. Keeping up with cybersecurity news, trends, and alerts. Find a few news sources you trust (can’t go wrong with Krebs on Security or CISA Alerts)

2. Find mentors in different areas of security, I had mentors on the red team, blue team, digital forensics, and a few other areas so I could ask about their experience directly before deciding if it was right for me

3. Getting certifications & continuous learning - I think cybersecurity is one of the most cert-heavy fields in tech and most roles, entry level or senior, will have some preferred/required experience for a certification. I started with the CompTIA Sec+ which is a great option for beginners/entry level!

4. Be wary of alert fatigue & burnout. You want to prioritize your mental and physical health above all else, at the end of the day, that’s the most important.

#cybersecurity #cybersecuritytraining #techjobs

This is probably one of the biggest life decisions I’ve ever made 🫣. When I quit my job a few months ago, I already knew we’d be prepping for this big move next year! It started out with planning my 5/10/15 year goals in 2019 when I graduated (influenced by all the self-help books I was reading lmao *ahem* 4-hour work week..) and the biggest thing on the list was to live abroad for a bit.

It was a pretty big goal with lots of question marks considering I was still trying to figure out how I’d be able to work across Asia esp working in cybersecurity where crossing regional borders can be an issue. But basically this was my guiding star and I set 2024 as the timeline. The biggest risk was that I’d be quitting my job and living off of savings and my income from YouTube which was pretty inconsistent at the time. But with some encouragement, I ended up quitting my job early this past summer and doing YouTube full-time (which btw I never thought would’ve been possible or even remotely sustainable as a source of income but somehow things have been working out??) I’m planning to use this time as a ~*career sabbatical*~ to try out this FT content creator thing and slow travel across Asia next year and I can’t wait to take you guys along 🥰🫶 (will share more once the date gets closer!) 

I’m also really grateful to have people in my life that push me and ask the important questions of “if not now, then when?” and “if you didn’t try it, would you regret it?”. Even if it’s switching careers, starting a YouTube channel, or just trying something new, you never know where that could lead you. Wishing you all the best 🩵

26 🤍 This year has been full of surprises and new experiences and I’m just really grateful for everything! My biggest goal for this next year is living more in the present, especially as we make our move abroad. Thanks for being here! 🦋
